<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Tietmeyer sees need for dollar stability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An excessive fall in the US dollar is damaging for everybody, Mr Hans
Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank president, said yesterday in a statement of
support for the US currency.
'The world economy has an interest in an internally and externally stable
dollar,' said yesterday in Frankfurt at a lunch held by the American Chamber
of Commerce.
The dollar, meanwhile, continued its cautious recovery on foreign exchanges
yesterday, helped by supportive comments from Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US
treasury secretary.
Mr Tietmeyer said the strengthening of the D-Mark against the US currency
this year was in part due to overreaction in financial markets, as well as
overdone fear of new inflation in the US. 'Unfortunately now and then there
are exaggerated developments in the foreign exchange markets, as seems to be
the case now with the dollar,' he said.
Although economists believe that a cut in short-term German interest rates -
particularly if coupled with an increase in US rates - would take the
pressure off the US economy, Mr Tietmeyer said yesterday: 'The prime
responsibility for the dollar's strength lies in the US itself.
'The thesis current at the beginning of the seventies - it's our currency
but your problem - is clearly too short-sighted. It didn't do the US much
good at the time either.'
He welcome the commitment of Mr Bentsen to a stronger dollar, as well as the
conclusion of G7 ministers at Naples that a further weakening would be
neither desirable nor justified.
He said that as yet the economic recovery in Europe had not been endangered
as a result of currency developments, and that in fact the latest
developments helped to hold costs down. Further export growth was dependent
on a lasting worldwide recovery, for which a central precondition was
lasting price stability, in the US as elsewhere.
He said a return to fixed interest rate systems would not work, nor would a
move to 'target zones' for currencies. Long-term fixed exchange rates could
only work with convergence of economic conditions, he argued, 'and at the
moment we are a long way from that - at least worldwide'.
Reviewing recent German interest rate policy, Mr Tietmeyer said the
Bundesbank had not given way to pressure for a forced, aggressive sinking of
interest rates. This would have had a negative impact in the markets.
Markets cautious, Page 5; See currencies and money page
</TEXT>
