<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Tesco offer for Wm Low may spark rival bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tesco, the UK's second largest supermarket chain, yesterday made a
recommended offer for William Low, the struggling Scottish retail food
group, in a deal worth Pounds 200m.
But J. Sainsbury, Tesco's bigger rival, signalled later yesterday that it
was considering its options, raising the prospect of a takeover battle for
the Scottish chain. Both Tesco and Sainsbury are keen to expand in Scotland.
Tesco is offering Pounds 154m in cash for the share capital of William Low
and would assume debt of just over Pounds 50m. The deal was unanimously
recommended by the William Low board.
Sainsbury entered the picture when it told Reuters: 'William Low is
something we have looked at before. It is an obvious candidate for takeover
and has been for some time. As a result of this morning's takeover news we
are reviewing the situation.'
Sainsbury later told the Stock Exchange that it was requesting information
from William Low and was considering its position.
Analysts said it would be out of character for Sainsbury to become involved
in a hostile takeover battle, particularly since the Tesco bid has the
backing of the William Low board.
Sainsbury has only four outlets north of the border - three supermarkets and
one hypermarket. Tesco said its 16 Scottish stores would be a good strategic
fit with William Low's 45 outlets in Scotland and 12 in the north of
England.
Strong competition from discount retailers and larger food chains has cut
William Low's profit margins, and its sales are currently 5 per cent below
last year's levels.
Tesco said there would be few, if any, immediate closures of William Low
stores. But it would be necessary to integrate the management and support
services provided by just over 300 people working at the company's Dundee
head office into Tesco's administration.
'Accordingly, there may be a significant number of job lossesif the head
office were to close,' Tesco said.
Tesco added it would offer relocation opportunities and give generous
redundancy terms if the takeover went ahead.
Sir Ian MacLaurin, the Scot who is chairman of Tesco, said the deal would be
good for shareholders of both groups.
The William Low outlets would be renamed Tesco, but he said an effort would
be made to develop a distinctive Scottish identity - perhaps using a Tesco
Scotland brand.
The group would spend Pounds 35m on rebranding the existing William Low
stores and introducing its own-label products. Tesco said its prices were on
average 5 per cent lower than William Low's, thanks partly to the economies
of scale achievable by the bigger group.
Tesco is offering 225p in cash for each William Low ordinary share and
105.5p for each convertible preference share.
There is a full share alternative, worth 236p per ordinary share at last
night's close.
William Low's shares rose by 67p to 236p, while Tesco's shares closed 10 1/2
p higher at 232 1/2 p. Tesco is advised by BZW and William Low by Barings.
Lex, Page 16; Background, Page 17; London stocks, Page 36
</TEXT>
