<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Rifkind cuts 18,000 defence jobs: RAF faces heaviest
personnel losses - Blow softened by weapons orders for Pounds 5bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, BERNARD GRAY and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 18,000 British defence jobs are to be cut, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the
UK defence secretary, said yesterday, but he softened the blow by announcing
orders for new weapons worth about Pounds 5bn.
His announcement, which drew angry protests from opposition parties and
trade unions, marked the conclusion of an eight-month study designed to cut
Pounds 750m from the annual defence budget from 1997 onwards.
Mr Rifkind told the Commons the cost-saving drive would make no difference
to Britain's fighting strength and the money saved would enable some
upgrading of capacity. The heaviest job losses will be in the Royal Air
Force which will lose 7,500 personnel, while another 7,100 civilian jobs are
to go.
To offset the job losses, Mr Rifkind announced firm orders for Pounds 2.4bn
tenders for additional hardware worth a similar amount.
'The orders will preserve and enhance our fighting strength and help sustain
over 10,000 jobs,' Mr Rifkind said. 'Our plans for the armed forces reflect
the challenges we are likely to face. We are determined to maintain that
position and not drop our guard.'
Mr David Clark, Labour's defence spokesman, rejected the contention that
fighting strength was unimpaired. He said that in the event of war 'today's
short-term financial savings could cost British lives'.
Mr Rifkind announced orders for seven new minehunters for the Royal Navy,
259 Challenger-2 tanks for the army and a substantial upgrading of 142
Tornado aircraft in service with the RAF.
Further orders will follow, including two new Royal Marine assault ships to
replace HMS Fearless and HMS Intrepid, a further batch of three Type 23
frigates and up to six Trafalgar class nuclear submarines. The MoD also
confirmed that the royal dockyards at Devonport and Rosyth are to be
privatised.
Several smaller RAF stations, including RAF Pitreavie in Fife, Scampton in
Lincolnshire and Finningley in Yorkshire are to close, but the naval base at
Rosyth is to remain open with a reduced role.
Its ships are to be assigned to Faslane on the Clyde and Portsmouth in
Hampshire, and 700 jobs will be lost at the base with an additional 1,500
naval personnel moved elsewhere. Some 900 jobs will remain.
The cuts go to the highest level in the forces with some 20 military and
civil service posts of the rank of major general or above being abolished.
At the Ministry of Defence headquarters in London, a further 1,500 jobs are
to go and two buildings are to close.
Some 500 jobs will go at the defence procurement executive in Bristol.
Logistic support is being rationalised with the closure of 17 stores and the
loss of 1,500 jobs.
Many of the orders spelt out yesterday had been expected for some time.
However, Mr Rifkind made a surprise announcement that, in the light of
experience in the Gulf war, the UK would be ordering laser-guided Paveway 3
bombs from the US manufacturer Texas Instruments.
It was also opening negotiations with the US government to buy the Tomahawk
cruise missile. These 'smart' munitions proved particularly effective in the
Gulf.
Mr Rifkind also announced that a frigate and a submarine which were
previously to have been mothballed would be retained in active service.
A joint service rapid deployment force, including paratroopers, marines and
RAF aircraft, is to be formed.
Several new institutions to be used by all three services will replace
single-service facilities.
Senior officers had apparently opposed the emphasis on tri-service
operations, but ministers regarded it as an important change.
Aftershock reverberates across the industry, Page 10
Editorial Comment and Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
