<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Collection of factors combine
to lift Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Reassuring news on inflation, a modest rebound in the dollar and news of
another bid for the QVC television shopping group lifted US share prices
across the board for much of yesterday, though prices eventually ended
little changed on the day, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 1.62 up at 3704.28, having shown
double-digit gains through the morning. The more broadly based Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 was also slightly firmer, up 0.78 at 448.73, while the American
Stock Exchange composite was up 2.23 at 427.73 and the Nasdaq composite up
9.76 at 719.35. Trading volume stood at 265,000 shares.
Share prices firmed from the opening, helped by news that the consumer price
index had risen by only 0.3 per cent last month. Although the CPI number was
not as positive as the report on the producer prices index, which was flat
last month, it was in line with expectations, and reassured investors who
had been worried that strong second quarter economic growth might have fed
through into higher prices. Also, taken together, the June inflation data
was unlikely to prompt the Federal Reserve into raising interest rates
again.
Consequently, stocks posted solid gains in early trading, rising by more
than 20 points at one stage. Equities received no help from bonds, which
ignored the good inflation news. By late in the day, the 30-year bond was
barely changed, yielding 7.67 per cent.
A modest rally in the dollar, which rebounded a yen to Y98.35 and more than
a pfennig to DM1.5422, did help stock market sentiment, however. Later in
the day, blue chip prices gave up most of their gains on a lack of
follow-through buying.
Nasdaq stocks outperformed other sectors of the market thanks to strong
technology stocks, and news of a rival bid for QVC. Last week the home
shopping television group announced that it was merging with CBS, the
broadcast television network. Late on Tuesday night, however, Comcast, the
big telecommunications group which owns 15.4 per cent of QVC, launched a
counter bid worth Dollars 2.2bn.
The rival offer immediately persuaded CBS to abandon its merger plans, which
did not deter investors from buying QVC in the hope that the stock's price
would be driven higher by new bids for the company. By the close, QVC was up
Dollars 6 at Dollars 42 in volume of 7.3m shares. Comcast, which is also
traded on the Nasdaq market, was down Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 15 1/8 in
volume of 7.4m shares.
On the New York SE, CBS shares were also higher, up Dollars 8 at Dollars
308, although the rise in the stock had less to do with the news of its
failed merger with QVC and more to do with the company's plans, announced
yesterday, to buy in 3.5m of its own shares and split the stock
five-for-one.
Hilton Hotels rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 62 7/8 after reporting second
quarter profits of Dollars 33.9m, up 26 per cent from a year ago.
Among higher Nasdaq technology stocks, Intel was up Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars
61 3/4 , Cisco Systems Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 24, Lotus Development
Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 40 1/2 , and Oracle Dollars  5/8 higher at Dollars
39 5/8 .
Canada
Toronto posted a small gain in dull dealings. The TSE-300 composite index
gained 8.83 points, or 0.21 per cent, to 4,140.55, as advances were led
declines by 371 to 336. Volume rose to 56.15m shares compared with 43.91m on
Tuesday.
Despite the overall market gain, just five of the 14 sub-indices ended
higher, including industrial products with a 1.71 per cent index gain.
Energy was up slightly, consumer products and mining were flat. Financial
services was a bit lower and golds fell 0.85 per cent.
Newbridge Networks continued its sharp climb, rising 2 3/8 to 59 7/8 . The
company late Monday announced a buy-back of up to 4m shares, and was up 2
7/8 yesterday.
Mexico
Mexican stocks closed lower after an apathetic session, affected by an
increase in domestic interest rates. The IPC index of 37 leading shares
closed 23.31 points lower at 2,264.97, a drop of 1.02 per cent.
'The market is still dead as far as volume is concerned,' one analyst said.
'The increase in domestic interest rates may well be the most influential
factor, since a rise was expected but nothing so big or so across the
board,' a trader added.
</TEXT>
