<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / International Company News: Advertising sales boost Gannett
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Improved newspaper advertising revenues and steady operating costs helped
Gannett, the US publishing and broadcasting group, report record after-tax
profits of Dollars 131.8m, or 90 cents a share, in the second quarter.
A year before, net income was Dollars 113.6m, or 78 cents.
Gannett, whose publications includes USA Today, earned advertising revenue
of Dollars 540m in the period, up from Dollars 513m, while income from
newspaper circulation edged up Dollars 3m to Dollars 213m. Other sources of
revenue were broadly in line with the year before, while costs, excluding
interest payments, were flat at Dollars 736m.
The company, which publishes 83 newspapers across the US, attributed the
advance to gains in 'help-wanted' advertising. The 13 per cent increase in
classified advertising sales contributed to a 5 per cent overall gain in
newspaper advertising revenues, it said.
Broadcasting revenues fell slightly, to Dollars 107m, reflecting the sale of
three radio stations. However, profits climbed 29 per cent to Dollars 39m.
Profits from outdoor advertising, by contrast, slid 8 per cent to Dollars
8.2m, as revenues fell 1 per cent to Dollars 63m
For the first half, net income of Dollars 210m, or Dollars 1.43 a share, was
up from Dollars 180m, or Dollars 1.23, a year before.
Higher revenues in its information services business were behind a 16 per
cent rise in net income at Dow Jones in the second quarter.
The company, whose interests include the Wall Street Journal, said revenues
from information services such as the Dow Jones/Telerate services, rose 12
per cent to Dollars 239m.
Net income was Dollars 46m, or 46 cents a share, for the period, and Dollars
86m, or 86 cents, for the first half of 1994. These compare with Dollars
40m, or 40 cents, and Dollars 71m or 71 cents last time.
</TEXT>
