<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / International Company News: Bilfinger &amp; Berger emerges as
Buderus shareholder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bilfinger &amp; Berger, one of Germany's largest construction groups, yesterday
emerged as the surprise owner of a 15 per cent stake in Buderus, the German
heating equipment and engineering group.
The news follows last month's placing of 80 per cent of Buderus on the
German stock exchanges by Metallgesellschaft, the troubled conglomerate.
Buderus shares were suspended yesterday.
The move is widely seen in Germany as a prelude to a possible battle for
control of the highly profitable Buderus. Both Commerzbank and Dresdner Bank
each have a 10 per cent stake in the engineering group.
Mr Christian Roth, Bilfinger chairman, disclosed the news of the
shareholding at Bilfinger's annual meeting yesterday. He said that Bilfinger
was in talks with Buderus management board.
Although a Buderus official statement said that it welcomed Bilfinger as a
long-term shareholder, Mr Reinhard Engel, a director of Buderus, said there
had been no talks with Bilfinger and there was no possibility of business
co-operation.
'There is no evidence to suggest that there is anything suspicious about
this holding,' said Mr Engel. 'We see it in a neutral light: we are not
enthusiastic but we are not disappointed either.'
Secret stake-building is shortly to become illegal in Germany under the
terms of the Finanzmarktforderungsgesetz, the second Financial Markets
Promotion Act, which is likely to come into force on August 1. The law will
oblige companies to disclose stakes once they reach 5 per cent, providing an
early warning system for German companies. There are no takeover rules in
Germany akin to the UK Takeover Code.
The stake-building also appears to contradict the terms of the placing of
Buderus shares last month, in which Metallgesellschaft obtained DM1.2bn
(Dollars 788m) for its 80 per cent shareholding.
Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank arranged the placing of Metallgesellschaft's
Buderus stake with the declared aim of ensuring that Buderus would be owned
by a broad spread of shareholders.
Deutsche Bank said it had been told about Bilfinger's purchases yesterday by
Dresdner, a 25 per cent shareholder in Bilfinger. Dresdner refused to answer
specific questions about its role in helping Bilfinger buy the Buderus
shares.
Buderus made pre-tax profits of DM133m (Dollars 81.5m) last year on sales of
DM2.77bn.
</TEXT>
