<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / International Company News: Japan's chip makers step up
capital spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japanese semiconductor makers are stepping up capital spending on
manufacturing facilities to meet growing demand from the computer and home
electronics markets.
NEC, the second largest maker of semiconductors in the world after Intel of
the US, plans to increase capital spending on chip production this year to
Y110bn (Dollars 1.1bn). It had earlier set spending at Y90bn.
Fujitsu is also increasing capital spending by Y18bn while Mitsubishi
Electric is considering raising investment in order to meet an expected
surge in demand in years ahead.
Meanwhile, Toshiba, which is Japan's second largest semiconductor maker,
announced that a joint venture semiconductor manufacturing company it has
with Motorola of the US, is investing about Y27bn in a new facility in Japan
to make microprocessors and application specific integrated circuits
(ASICs).
The increased investments reflect the strong demand for semiconductors from
not only the computer market but the home electronics and audio visual
markets in Japan, the companies said.
'Our factories are being squeezed to the pip,' said Mr Mark Pearce, of NEC.
The move in the PC market towards advanced computers and the introduction of
new operating software have increased demand for memory chips, NEC said. The
new operating software, for example, uses more than ten times the memory
required to run earlier software.
At the same time, however, demand for semiconductors from home electronics
makers has also been strong particularly for microcontrollers that go into
products such as mobile phones, air conditioners, washing machines and other
household appliances.
The trend reflects both the growing use in such household appliances of
microcontrollers and a recovery in consumer spending.
</TEXT>
