<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong evening for factual programmes. In The Business David Lomax reports
on the economic success of Taiwan and discovers that education plays a major
role in the country's expansion: the constitution requires 15 per cent of
the government budget to be spent on education (7.30 BBC2). That is followed
by another in the Hypotheticals series in which role playing is used to
investigate some hypothetical conundrum. Today's subject: patient
confidentiality (8.00 BBC2). A new series of QED begins by investigating the
recent incidence of streptococcus A which gave rise to the 'Killer bug ate
my face' stories in the tabloid papers (8.00 BBC1). If the other programmes
in the State Of The Ark series are as effective as the opening episode, this
will be a very strong series indeed. Today's programme tries to establish
what constitutes a 'good' zoo (9.30 BBC2). Previous efforts by Nigel Planer
to satirise aspects of showbusiness have tended to be heavy handed. Tonight
he begins a sitcom, Wake Up With .. in which he plays co-host on one of
those daytime sofa shows. Encouragingly the writer is Andrew Nickolds (8.30
ITV).
</TEXT>
