<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / Survey of Merseyside (4): Unfinished business - Merseyside
Development Corporation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This has not been a good year for the Merseyside Development Corporation. It
is under a cloud because of a debacle over a loss-making opera concert
staged to celebrate the visit of the Columbus Grand Regatta tall ships in
1992.
Mr Chris Farrow, the chief executive, has been grilled by the Commons public
accounts committee over the concert's Pounds 695,000 losses; its report is
awaited nervously by the corporation.
In the meantime, the MDC is having a row with the Mersey Docks and Harbour
Company over development of a ro-ro container terminal at Birkenhead, where
the MDC has planning powers.
The dock company offered immediate development at a cost of up to Pounds
20m, but the MDC has made London &amp; General Property its preferred developer
on its Pounds 70m, more visionary but less certain proposals for a container
terminal, a science park and a student village.
Mr Bob Lane, the MDC's assistant chief executive, says: 'This met the wider
brief that we wanted. We are in the business of job creation. A dock by
itself would not have created many jobs.'
London &amp; General has to produce detailed proposals by the end of this month,
and the deal might still fall through, but the row has been a poor
advertisement for Merseyside's claim that all is now sweetness and light
between public and private sectors.
The pity is that these difficulties have overshadowed the fact that the sums
finally seem to be coming right for the MDC, 13 years after it was founded -
alongside its London counterpart - to bring disused Mersey docklands back
from the dead.
By 1990, the MDC had spent Pounds 180m of public money but had generated
only Pounds 43.5m in private sector investment. Its policy of leisure
development - notably the Albert Dock tourist complex - was criticised for
attracting 5m visitors a year who did not spend enough to create many jobs.
The figures, however, are now better. Total private sector investment is put
at Pounds 301m, slightly ahead of the cumulative total for spending by the
corporation. Since most of the corporation money was spent in the early
years, anything new from the private sector should now push up the multiple
of private to public sector investment rapidly.
The corporation has reclaimed more than 800 acres of land, built 468,000 sq
ft of office space and, most important of all, helped create 10,605 jobs.
There are three pieces of unfinished business before wind-up in 1998. The
corporation wants to help develop derelict land in north Liverpool and
Bootle and plans to spend Pounds 30m making the rest of the A565 Southport
road into a dual carriageway.
Another big project will be the former Cammell Laird shipyard, where English
Partnerships hopes to get EU Objective 1 funding for development with the
MDC and private sector.
A question-mark hangs over the third project, involving King's Dock, next to
the Albert Dock on the Liverpool waterfront. A grand design has been set out
for leisure and business space, but so far developers have not come forward
for the 40-acre site.
However, despite the inquiry into the tall ships fiasco and doubts about
whether there is enough demand to drive projects involving offices and
science parks, the corporation should end its life with a reputation for a
job pretty well done.
</TEXT>
