<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / Mercury in row over network fee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A war of words erupted yesterday between Mr Don Cruickshank, the
telecommunications regulator, and Mercury, the main competitor to British
Telecommunications, over payments the company has to make to BT for the use
of its network.
In unusually strong language for a regulator, Mr Cruickshank condemned as
'unnecessary and shrill' recent Mercury statements about the unfairness of
the regulatory regime.
However, Ms Maev Sullivan, Mercury's director of strategy, cited remarks of
Mr Cruickshank's in March in support of her view that payments made by
Mercury to BT for the loss it makes on its local network amounted to a 'tax
on competition'. She said Mr Cruickshank had said that the payments - called
'access deficit contributions' - would come to look like an accounting
fiction.
Oftel said the remarks referred to the case for greater transparency in BT's
accounts, a policy it is currently pursuing.
The dispute came as Mr Cruickshank announced a two-year exemption from the
payments for eight new operators in the UK.
Until March 1996 the operators - ACC, Worldcom, Colt, MFS, Energis,
Telewest, Videotron and Nynex - are unlikely to have to pay BT to help cover
the estimated Pounds 1.45bn it lost last year on maintaining its local
network. The loss is incurred because BT is not allowed to raise its line
rental and connection charges in line with its local network costs.
Under the terms of BT's licence, Oftel can grant waivers to operators,
provided their traffic does not exceed 15 per cent in each of the UK's
international and national telecoms markets. The maximum value of the
waivers to other operators is about Pounds 150m.
Mr Cruickshank said the waivers would 'assist new entrants to establish
themselves in the UK'. But he committed himself to a broad review of the
future of access deficit contributions, which was welcomed by Mercury.
Some analysts were surprised at Oftel's decision to grant waivers to
operators competing largely or exclusively in the international market. They
attributed the move to Oftel's desire to persuade US authorities of the
openness of the UK telecoms market.
Mercury has paid more than Pounds 50m in access deficit contributions in
respect of its international calls. It is estimated to have more than 20 per
cent of the UK's international market, but it is unlikely this year to reach
the level at which it would have to make payments for its domestic traffic.
Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
