<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / MPs demand more cash for primary education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government should increase funding for primary schools, a cross-party
Commons committee recommended yesterday.
It said that 'any real-terms increase in funding that becomes available,
from either national or local government' should be distributed
'disproportionately in favour of primary schools'.
There should also be a small annual shift in funding between the sectors,
moving towards a common pupil-teacher ratio for both. The committee said
that at present there was 'insufficient support time' for teachers in
primary schools, where there are 22.21 pupils to each teacher, compared with
15.83 in secondary schools.
An average of 40 per cent more is spent on each English secondary pupil than
for each primary pupil.
The report said: 'If any particular phase of school education is funded at a
disproportionately low level, children of all ages will suffer, and in the
long run the nation as a whole suffers.'
Unions gave the report a strong welcome, but said that funds for secondary
schools should not be cut. The government welcomed the report as a
contribution to debate.
The government intends to spread the common funding formula for
grant-maintained secondary schools to another 16 local authorities next
year. It will add to the incentives for schools still with those local
authorities to opt out.
Under the formula grant-maintained schools are paid the funding they would
have received if their local authority had spent as much on education as was
predicted by the government's standard spending assessment, even if the
authority spends less than that official assessment. But if the council
spends more than its assessment the formula allows for opted-out schools to
be paid more.
The 16 authorities, in all of which 30 per cent of secondary pupils are
taught in grant-maintained schools, are: Barnet, Brent, Cambridgeshire,
Croydon, Cumbria, Ealing, Enfield, Hertfordshire, Kent,
Kingston-upon-Thames, Lambeth, Lincolnshire, Southwark, Sutton, Wandsworth,
and Wiltshire.
The Disparity in Funding Between Primary and Secondary Schools, House of
Commons Education Committee. HMSO. Pounds 12.15.
</TEXT>
<XX>
