FT  14 JUL 94 / BBC may buy more shows from external producers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC is considering buying more television programmes from ITV, Channel 4
and independent producers, Mr Bob Phillis, deputy director-general said at a
London media conference yesterday.
The corporation, which already has programme deals with Granada and Central,
two of the largest ITV companies, is seeking flexibility in programme supply
in the wake of last week's white paper, which promised it more commercial
freedom.
Mr Phillis also told the conference, organised by the Labour party, that he
would not rule out wider co-operation with ITV companies in particular
regions or on launching new satellite channels.
The BBC has already announced a strategic alliance with Pearson, the media
group that owns the Financial Times, with the intention of launching two
satellite channels for Europe this year. These will feature news and
entertainment but the corporation is also looking at specialist channels in
areas such as education and documentaries.
Mr Phillis said some ITV companies had great expertise in areas the BBC was
interested in developing.
He also told the conference that the corporation had set up a further study
of digital terrestrial television which would be completed by March.
The government last week linked the possible privatisation of BBC
transmission services with the launch of new digital channels.
Mr Phillis said yesterday: 'Our concerns are to ensure the most reliable and
cost-effective service for our audiences and we will judge any possible
changes on that basis.'
