<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / World Cup '94: Brazil in final thanks to Romario
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's 24-year wait for a place in the World Cup final ended yesterday
when they beat Sweden 1-0 in the Pasadena Rose Bowl to set up a rematch of
the 1970 final in Mexico against Italy, when a Pele-inspired Brazil won 4-1.
Barcelona striker Romario headed home the only goal ten minutes from the end
after Brazil had dominated much of the match, only to be frustrated by some
inspired goalkeeping by Thomas Ravelli, but more by their own inability to
finish countless chances.
Romario should have put Brazil ahead in the 26th minute after Branco's
through ball split the Swedish defence, but the attacker waited too long to
shoot and Patrik Andersson scrambled the ball off the goalline. Mazinho then
smashed the rebound into the side netting.
Bebeto sent Romario clear with a brilliant flick 7 minutes later but he
stumbled over the ball, allowed Ravelli to head him off and shot into the
side of the net.
Sweden created very few chances in the first half, seemingly content to rely
on long, high balls, which were largely ineffective.
The Swedes, trying to get to the final for the first time since Brazil beat
them in 1958, had their captain Jonas Thern sent off in the 63rd minute for
a bad challenge on Dunga.
The ten men defended well and looked for a break from set-pieces, but the
Brazilian forwards wore them down and Romario's fifth goal of the tournament
deflated the Scandinavians. In Sunday's final, both Italy and Brazil will be
going for a record fourth World Cup title. Of the two, Italy was last to win
it in 1982.
Third-Place Play-Off
Saturday
Bulgaria vs Sweden
Los Angeles, 8.30pm BST
Final
Sunday
Italy vs Brazil
Los Angeles 8.30pm
</TEXT>
