FT  14 JUL 94 / UN in Dollars 540m Sarajevo project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Despite the uncertain prospects for peace in Bosnia-Hercegovina, work is
about to begin on a Dollars 540m (Pounds 343m) UN co-ordinated action plan
for the restoration of essential services to Sarajevo, United Nations
officials said yesterday. Nearly half the money is needed for projects
described as 'urgent' and scheduled for completion by the end of this year.
Immediate priorities include restoration of the city's gas supply, water
chlorination, refuse removal, restoration of power lines and repairs to
schools in time for the autumn term. Mr Edouard Rousselot, operations
director for the action plan, said more than Dollars 68m had already been
raised following a pledging conference in New York at the end of June, the
three largest donors so far being the US, Britain and Japan. The action plan
relates to 'greater' Sarajevo, including Bosnian Serb-controlled areas.
