<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 94 / Whitehall faces sweeping reform: Government outlines
four-year plan to cut 50,000 civil service jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's government yesterday pushed its campaign for an improved
public service to the very heart of Whitehall with plans for the most
comprehensive restructuring of the civil service in decades.
In a long-awaited white paper, the government outlined a set of reforms
which will reduce the size of the civil service by about 50,000 people over
the next four years and expose Whitehall to management practices that are
commonplace in the private sector.
The reforms will give individual Whitehall departments more autonomy over
the selection of senior staff and the determination of running costs. It is
proposed that more senior civil service posts should be open to candidates
from the private sector and that the salaries of senior officials should be
partly linked to their performance.
Departments will also be obliged to introduce a fundamental reform of
accounting practice, monitoring capital expenditure more comprehensively.
Presenting the white paper to the House of Commons, Mr William Waldegrave,
the public service minister, said the aim of the reforms was to 'map a way
forward for the civil service to the end of the century and beyond', making
the Whitehall structure 'tauter and flatter' than it is now.
However, he also acknowledged that the civil service had a 'unique role' in
maintaining Britain's unwritten constitution. He assured MPs that the
government would adopt a bipartisan approach to its proposals, and would
consult opposition parties before implementing them.
Some Labour MPs believed the proposals were far less radical than Mr
Waldegrave might have wished, and that some cabinet ministers had ensured
that the apparatus of government would remain in its traditional shape.
'The consolidators have won,' said Mr Giles Radice, who chairs inquiries
into Whitehall by the Treasury and civil service select committee. 'This is
not a radical document and the chance to open up the civil service has not
really been taken.' At the heart of the proposals is the creation of a
Senior Civil Service, which will be composed of the top 3,500 officials.
It is proposed that these officials should receive explicit written
employment contracts for the first time, and that salaries should be partly
based on performance. Fixed term contracts could be used but ministers
underlined that these would be in exceptional cases.
Mr Waldegrave said open competition for posts 'should become a more normal
part of the process of selecting people for senior appointments'. But the
white paper failed to outline any specific targets for such appointments.
The accounting reforms, outlined in a Treasury green paper yesterday,
proposed that all government departments comply with radically different
accounting practices more in line with the private sector within the next
four years.
The planned switch from cash-based to 'accruals' accounting will impose for
the first time on the civil service the need to account for capital
expenditure and to develop a series of more accurate management indicators.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said: 'This is a highly significant event
that will make a great different to how government carries out business,
makes decisions and is made accountable.'
Mr Noel Hepworth, director of the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and
Accountancy, said: 'This is good news. It is part of a continuum of steps to
improve the quality of management of government services.'
Tory revolution reaches Whitehall, Page 9
Changes urged for 'fast-stream' entry, Page 9
Labour attacks plan, Page 9
Editorial Comment, Page 25
</TEXT>
