<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Good inflation data fails to
lift US stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
After good news on inflation had failed to lift stock market sentiment
during the morning, a rebound in bond prices and a modest rally in the
dollar helped share prices end flat-to-firmer yesterday, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 0.33 at 3,702.66,
well above its low for the day of 3,672.24. The more broadly-based Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 ended down 0.11 at 447.95, while the American Stock Exchange
composite finished up 0.73 at 425.50 and the Nasdaq composite up 2.76 at
709.59. Trading volume was 252m shares.
Stock prices inched higher at the opening, encouraged by early gains in
bonds which were sparked by reassuring news on inflation. The Labor
department had reported that the producer prices index had remained flat
during June, and that 'core' producer prices - the index excluding the
volatile food and energy components - had actually fallen by 0.1 per cent.
The figures were better than economists had been expecting, and provided an
early boost to bond prices. At one stage, the benchmark 30-year bond was up
three quarters of a point. Those early gains were wiped out later in the
day, as bonds retreated in the wake of another big drop in the dollar, which
fell to a new post-1945 low against the yen of Y96.50. At one point, the Dow
was more than 20 points lower, as investors feared that the losses in the
dollar might push the Federal Reserve into raising interest rates again to
support the ailing currency.
The sell-off in bonds, however, did not last long. Thanks to a modest rally
in the dollar, which moved up to Y97.43 in late trading, and a
weaker-than-expected report on retail sales from the Johnson Redbook
service, the 30-year bond rebounded more than three quarters of a point from
its lows. Stocks quickly followed suit, although blue-chip issues struggled
to move into positive territory, primarily because in the past week
blue-chips have outperformed other sectors of the market.
Among individual stocks, Motorola jumped Dollars 5 1/2 to Dollars 50 1/4 as
investors responded positively to Monday night's news that the company had
earned 63 cents a share, up from a comparable 40 cents a share a year ago,
and that semiconductor sales rose 23 per cent in the April-to-June period.
Goodyear fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 35 in volume of 1.8m shares after the
company's chairman, Mr Stanley Gault, said in a television interview that
Goodyear's earnings in the second quarter would come in between Dollars 158m
and Dollars 164m. Although that would represent a record quarter for the
company, investors were disappointed because industry analysts had been
looking for slightly better results.
Philip Morris dropped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 53 1/8 in heavy trading after
the tobacco and foods group announced second quarter earnings of Dollars
1.2bn. Although that was up from Dollars 1.05bn a year earlier, the results
from the food operations were disappointing and a large part of the growth
in sales volume was due to adjustments in inventory levels.
Diagnostek rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 20 1/2 after being awarded a
contract from the defence department which could generate Dollars 100m in
annual revenues.
Canada
Toronto prices closed with a solid gain in moderate trading. The TSE-300
composite index gained 27.78 points, or 0.68 per cent, to close at 4,131.72.
Winning issues led losers by 377 to 327.
Activity continued at a relatively modest pace, with 43.91m shares changing
hands valued at CDollars 567m compared with 42.06m worth CDollars 515m on
Monday.
The industrial products sector led today's advance with a 1.87 per cent
index gain. In all, 12 of the 14 sub-groups were higher. Among the other key
groups, mining and energy were higher, financial services was up modestly,
while consumer products was little changed and golds fell somewhat.
Alcan Aluminium was up  1/4 to 33  3/8 in active trading after reporting its
first quarterly profit in nearly three years. Second-quarter net was Dollars
7m.
</TEXT>
