<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / World Commodities Prices: Chinese sales hit copper - Market
report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Persistent Chinese selling of COPPER gradually undermined market sentiment
at the London Metal Exchange and sent prices lower late yesterday. The three
months delivery price, which had earlier reached Dollars 2,454 a tonne,
closed at Dollars 2,449.50, up Dollars 5 on balance.
'This is a poor close, although the Chinese were looking to buy just under
the market,' one trader commented.
Three months ALUMINIUM came under liquidation pressure when it became
apparent it was not going to hold above the Dollars 1,550 resistance level
that was briefly breached in the morning.
At the London Commodity Exchange robusta COFFEE futures reversed early
losses after see-sawing wildly on thin volume as the market awaited fresh
news on the Brazilian frost damage. The September position closed at Dollars
3,898 a tonne, up Dollars 58.
'Trade and fund buying this afternoon on thin volume caught the market by
surprise and the sellers backed off,' one trader explained.
Compiled from Reuter
