<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / International Company News: Alliant Techsystems in Dollars
465m defence purchase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Alliant Techsystems, a Minnesota-based defence company, has agreed to pay
Dollars 465m in cash and shares for the aerospace and defence business of
Hercules, a company whose interests also extend to food additives and
specialty chemicals.
The deal is intended to create a stronger combined business in the defence
and aerospace businesses, the two companies said, and echoes other mergers
which have followed recent cuts in the US defence budget.
Hercules Aerospace, which had sales of Dollars 660m and operating profits of
Dollars 105m in 1993, makes rocket motors for space exploration, weapons
systems and ordnance for the US army. Alliant, with sales of Dollars 775m
and operating profits of Dollars 39m in the year to March 31, makes
munitions and marine systems for the US and other countries.
Under the agreement, Alliant will pay Dollars 365m in cash and issue 3.5m
new shares to Hercules. Alliant's shares fell Dollars 1 1/4 yesterday to
Dollars 28 5/8 . Over time, the company said, it will buy back 3.5m of its
shares in the open market to counter the effects of the deal.
The transaction will leave Hercules with a 26 per cent interest in Alliant,
and two seats on its board.
According to Mr Toby Warson, Alliant's president and chief executive, a
significant attraction of the deal is the ability to combine the two
companies' propellant production activities.
Northrop Grumman has reached an agreement with Carlyle Group to acquire
Carlyle's 51 per cent stake in Vought Aircraft for Dollars 130m, taking
Northrop Grumman's ownership to 100 per cent. The agreement is subject to
completion of a definitive agreement and Rodino anti-trust review.
</TEXT>
