<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Large parts of this evening's schedule on BBC1 and ITV will be occupied by
the semi-final matches in The World Cup. If the light of your life seizes
the remote control and insists upon spending hours watching men booting a
bladder around the park, do not despair; there are treats to be found
elsewhere. The opera relayed Live From Covent Garden on Radio 3 is
Massenet's 'Manon', with Romanian soprano Leontina Vaduva returning to the
title role which won her the 1988 award for most outstanding contribution to
opera. The story (of people always on the brink of taking holy orders, but
meanwhile having a ripping time) is told in five acts. In the first interval
James Naughtie interviews conductor Colin Davies (6.55). If your tastes run
more to folk music, Instrument And Tradition brings together folk fiddlers
from around the world (8.00 Radio 2). Fin de Siecle investigates the state
of Britain after the Wars Of The Roses (8.45 Radio 4). And Robert Robinson
begins a new series of his programme Ad Lib, this time in Australia, talking
to makers of Chardonnay (11.30 Radio 4).
</TEXT>
